    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-multiplication-law-of-indices">
        <title>Multiplication law of indices</title>
        <p>
            
        </p>
        
        <activity>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Work in Groups</alert>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Instructions</alert>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Use numbers between <m>1</m> and <m>9</m> to form at least three pairs of numbers that have the same base but different powers.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Multiply each pair that you have formed.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                For example: <m>2^2 \times 2^3</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Simplify each expression using the multiplication law of indices.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                For example: <m>2^2 \times 2^3 = 2^{2+3} = 2^5</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Discuss your work with your fellow learners.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </activity>
        <p>
            <term>Key Takeaway</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            
            The multiplication law of indices states that when you multiply two numbers with the same base, you add their exponents. 
            Mathematically this can be expressed  as:
            <m>a^m \times a^n = a^{m+n}</m>, where <m>a</m> is the base and <m>m</m>, <m>n</m> are the exponents.
        </p>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Simplify the following expressions:
                </p>
                <p>
                   a) <m>2^3 \times 2^4</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                   b) <m>8^3 \times 8^6</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                   a) Since the bases in <m>2^3 \times 2^4</m> are the same, we apply the multiplication law of indices:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> a^m \times a^n= \amp a^{m+n}</mrow>
                        <mrow> 2^3 \times 2^4= \amp 2^{3+4}</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 2^7</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                
                <p>
                    b) For <m>8^3 \times 8^6</m>, we have:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> 8^3 \times 8^6= \amp 8^{3+6}</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 8^9</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Evaluate: <m>4x^3 \times 7x^2</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    First, we multiply the coefficients (the numbers in front):
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>4 \times 7 = 28</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Next, we apply the multiplication law of indices to the variable <m>x</m>:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>x^3 \times x^2 = x^{3+2} = x^5</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, <me>
                        
                    </me>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> 4x^3 \times 7x^2 = \amp (4 \times 7)x^{3+2}</mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 28x^5 </mrow>
                    </md>
                     
                </p>
                
            </solution>
        </example>
         <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Simplify the expression <m>10^3 \times 10^{-2}</m>.
                </p>
            
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    To simplify this expression, we use the rule: <m>a^m \times a^n = a^{m+n}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> 10^3 \times 10^{-2} = \amp 10^{3+-2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp 10^1</mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 10 </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, <m>10^3 \times 10^{-2} = 10</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
        
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-division-law-of-indices">
        <title>Division law of indices</title>
       
        <activity>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Work in Groups</alert>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Instructions</alert>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               Using the division law of indices, work with the following pairs of numbers:
                            </p>
                            <p>
                               i) <m>5^2 , 5^1</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                               ii) <m>2^3, 2^5</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                               iii) <m>4^4, 4^8</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                iv) <m>6^6, 6^3</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               For each pair above, form a division expression.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                For example: <m>5^2 \div 5^1</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Apply the division law of indices to simplify each expression you created.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Create one division expression of your own using the law of indices. Simplify and calculate it.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Share your work with your fellow learners.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </activity>
        <p>
            <alert>Key Takeaway</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            The division law of indices states that when you divide two numbers with the same base, you subtract their exponents. 
             Mathematically this can be expressed as:
            <m>\frac{a^m}{a^n} = a^{m-n}</m>, where <m>a</m> is the base and <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> are the exponents.
        </p>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Simplify the following expressions:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\frac{5^6}{5^2}    </m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                 <m>\frac{10^5}{10^3}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                To solve for <m>\frac{5^6}{5^2}</m>, we apply the division law of indices <m>\frac{a^m}{a^n} = a^{m-n}</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Therefore, <me>
                                    
                                </me>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> \frac{5^6}{5^2} =\amp 5^{6-2}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> = \amp 5^4 </mrow>
                                </md>
                                
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                To solve <m>\frac{10^5}{10^3}</m>, we have:
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> \frac{10^5}{10^3}= \amp 10^{5-3}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> = \amp 10^2  </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Evaluate: <m>\frac{3x^5}{9x^2}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    First, we simplify the coefficients:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\frac{3}{9} = \frac{1}{3}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Next, we apply the division law of indices to the variable <m>x</m>:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\frac{x^5}{x^2} = x^{5-2} = x^3</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, <me>
                        
                    </me>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \frac{3x^5}{9x^2} = \amp \frac{1}{3}^{5-2}</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{3}x^3</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-brackets-with-indices">
        <title>Product of two powers</title>
        
        <activity>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Work in Groups</alert>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Instructions</alert>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Consider the following expressions.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <ol marker="a)" cols="3">
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                           <m>(2^3)^2</m> 
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>(3^2)^3</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>(5^1)^4</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>(4^2)^1</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>(10^2)^3</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>(7^3)^2</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ol>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Simplify the above expressions.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Share your work with your fellow learners.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </activity>
        <p>
            <alert>Key Takeaway</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
           Product of two powers happen when a term inside a bracket is raised to a power, and the whole bracket is also raised to another power. 
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Rule</alert>:<me>
                
            </me>
             <m>(a^m)^n = a^{m \times n} = a^{mn}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
           For example: <m>(a^2)^3 = a^{2 \times 3} = a^6</m> 
        </p>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Simplify the expression <m>(5^3)^3</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    To simplify <m>(5^3)^3</m> multiply the powers as shown below
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> (5^3)^3 = \amp 5^{3 \times}3</mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 5^9</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Hence, <m>(5^3)^3  = 5^9 </m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Solve the expression <m>(4y^2)^3</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Recall that <m>(a^m)^n = a^{m \times n} = a^{mn}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>(4y^2)^3 = \amp 4^3 \times (y^2)^3 </mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp 4^3 \times y^{2 \times 3} </mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp 4^3 \times y^6</mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 64y^6</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
    </subsubsection>
    
